    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1982-05-04T07:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1982-05-04T07:15:00-05:00" n="275"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d275">
                <head>275. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d275fn1"
                        >Source: Library of Congress, Manuscript Division, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HAM_1">Alexander Haig</persName> Papers, Department of
                        State, Day File, Box CL 77, 3–May 1982. Secret; Sensitive. No drafting
                        information appears on the memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1982-05-04T12:15:00+00:00">May 4, 1982, 12:15 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Mr. Bremer re Readout of Cabinet Meeting, China</item>
                </list>
                <p>The Secretary said that the Cabinet had reached a solution on the sugar quota
                    issue. We would take money from the quota system via agricultural committees to
                    compensate for <gloss target="#t_CBI_1">CBI</gloss> damage to Caribbean
                        nations.<note n="2" xml:id="d275fn2">An unknown hand wrote “<gloss
                            target="#t_CBI_1">CBI</gloss>” in the left-hand margin.</note> In other
                    words, it would be non-preferential and there would be no use of foreign
                    assistance funds. <persName corresp="#p_HRD_1">Hormats</persName> was to work
                    with <gloss target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss> and Treasury to put together the
                    package this afternoon; we needed to reestablish the President’s credibility.
                    The Secretary said this was a tight call for him. He knew somebody would come up
                    with something and therefore had played it the way he did.</p>
                <p>In a telephone conversation with <persName corresp="#p_ETO_1">Enders</persName>,
                    the Secretary outlined this new approach. He said that this did not require use
                    of foreign assistance money, but instead used tariff revenues. We could
                    compensate for the damaged Caribbean nations. It was under the jurisdiction of
                    agricultural committees rather than the House or Senate Foreign Affairs ones.
                    The Treasury proposal would not face us with the foreign assistance dilemma when
                    we could not get the money. The Secretary conceded that we would have gotten
                    rolled anyway.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of issues unrelated to sugar policy.]</p>
            </div>
